query:
title: RenamedFrom & Copilot Review

question: Regarding: [https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs-pr/pull/27165#discussion_r2933811826](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs-pr/pull/27165#discussion_r2933811826)

Previously the Azure SDK Bot recommended this pattern:

```
  @renamedFrom(Versions.v2026_05_01_preview, "reimage")
  @removed(Versions.v2026_05_01_preview)
  @sharedRoute
  reimageOld is ActionAsync<BareMetalMachine, void, OperationStatusResult>;

  @added(Versions.v2026_05_01_preview)
  @sharedRoute
  reimage is ActionAsync<
    BareMetalMachine,
    BareMetalMachineReimageParameters,
    OperationStatusResult,
    OptionalRequestBody = true
  >;
```


To change the body for my reimage action.

The copilot review has indicated the versioning decorators on `reimageOld` look internally inconsistent, and when I asked another copilot session, it said the pattern is correct.

Maybe the Agents can all get together an come to a consensus?

ground_truth:
A direct rename introduces a breaking change and should be avoided. In TypeSpec, use the version decorators `@removed` and `@added` to model the rename correctly without breaking older versions:

```
@removed(Versions.v2025_07_01)
captchaCookieExpirationInMins?: int32;

@added(Versions.v2025_07_01)
captchaExpirationInMins?: int32;
```

Make sure both versions are defined in `main.tsp`. After making this change, three things must still be addressed before merge:
- **TypeSpec validation**: run `tsp format .` to ensure all TypeSpec files are properly formatted.
- **SDK validation**: skip the .NET validation for now (it's not required and is being migrated to generate from TypeSpec); the Python SDK generation failure will be fixed by the team.
- **Breaking Change Review**: add the label `BreakingChange-Approved-Benign` or `BreakingChange-Approved-BugFix` based on your business requirements.

---

query:
title: ARM RPC Rule breaking : TopLevelResourcesListBySubscription

question: I introduced a new API version in my RP and added a new patch operation which returns a new model instead of the entire model response from a get/list api for that resource.
@added(Versions.v2026_02_01_preview)

interface RecommendationsPatch {

  /**

   * Update the state properties of a Recommendation.

   */

  @summary("Update the recommendation state properties.")

  @route("subscriptions/{subscriptionId}/providers/Microsoft.Advisor/recommendations/{recommendationId}")

  @patch(#{ implicitOptionality: false })

  patchStateProperties(

    ...ApiVersionParameter,

    ...SubscriptionIdParameter,

    /**

     * The recommendation ID.

     */

    @path

    recommendationId: string,

    /**

     * The properties to update the recommendation state.

     */

    @bodyRoot

    statePropertiesPayload: RecommendationsPatchPayload,

  ): ArmResponse<RecommendationsPatchPayload> | ArmDefaultErrorResponse;

@added(Versions.v2026_02_01_preview)

model RecommendationsPatchPayload

  extends Azure.ResourceManager.Foundations.Resource {

  /**

   * The properties for patch recommendation API.

   */

  properties?: RecommendationStatePropertiesPayload;

}

The PR has been active for a while as we are working on backend and we had already gotten the ARM Signed Off tag since all the checks passed. I recently made a small update in the PR to change some property names that are unrelated to this which caused the LintDiff to fail with TopLevelResourcesListBySubscription error. This check was not failing earlier. Can someone help me understand the reason for the sudden appearance of this when it was not failing earlier? I do not need to incorporate a list api that returns the full response that the list by subscription object would. This is a separate API we are introducing as per customer requirement.
[https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/pull/40288](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/pull/40288)
